Japan, India, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-04-10T22:53:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-10/japan-india-malaysia-singapore-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  Bank of Japan  will hold a quarterly branch managers’
meeting at 9:00 a.m. in Tokyo. Governor Masaaki Shirakawa will
give a speech around 9:30 a.m. and the bank will release a
regional economic report at 2:30 p.m.  Shirakawa will also speak at 6:00 p.m. at Imperial Hotel in
Tokyo.  Hiromasa Yonekura, chairman of Japan’s largest business
lobby, or Keidanren, will have a press briefing at 3:30 p.m. in
Tokyo.  The Cabinet Office is set to report the nation’s machine
orders in February at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo. Orders, an indicator
of business investment in three to six months, fell 0.9 percent
after increasing 4.2 percent in January, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.32 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 85.01 per dollar at 7:45 a.m. in Tokyo.  India : Industrial output increased 5 percent in February
from a year earlier, after a 3.7 percent gain in January,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists before official
data due today.  The yield on the benchmark 7.8 percent bond due May 2020
was 7.96 percent. The rupee was at 44.079 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell 2 billion ringgit
($662 million) of 210-day bills and 2 billion ringgit of 91-day
Islamic notes.  Industrial production grew 5.7 percent in February from a
year earlier, after a 1 percent gain the previous month,
according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg survey of
economists before data due today.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 4.08 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0165.  Singapore : The government will sell S$3.9 billion ($3.1
billion) of 91-day Treasury bills.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.46 percent. The  Singapore dollar  was at S$1.2572.  South Korea : The government will sell 2 trillion won ($1.8
billion) of five-year bonds.  The yield on the 5 percent bond due June 2020 was 4.47
percent. The won was at 1,083.03 per dollar.  Thailand : The Bank of Thailand will sell a combined 138
billion baht ($4.6 billion) of 15-, 24-, 87- and 178-day bills.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.21 percent. The baht was at 30.04 per dollar.  Taiwan: The government will sell NT$30 billion ($1 billion)
of 20-year bonds.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.35
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The  Taiwan
dollar  was at NT$28.991.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in Singapore at 
 kqayum@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
